{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/red-eye/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"5231497c-9015-54fd-b4f6-0c15ee18af82","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field a6668209-48c0-4008-bfbb-89b0237ca442 --><h1>Red eye: Summary</h1><!-- end field a6668209-48c0-4008-bfbb-89b0237ca442 -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 80994f4c-606c-4b3d-bf4a-9a833e4a1e3a --><!-- begin field 7fd9b01f-7666-4a57-9e79-c437efd6ae9b --><ul><li>There is a wide differential diagnosis for red eye. It is important to differentiate whether the person presenting with red eye needs same day assessment by an ophthalmologist, or if they can be safely managed in primary care. </li><li>Serious and potentially sight-threatening causes of red eye include:<ul><li>Acute glaucoma.</li><li>Corneal ulcer, contact lens-related red eye and corneal foreign body.</li><li>Anterior uveitis.</li><li>Scleritis.</li><li>Trauma, such as penetrating eye injury or high-velocity foreign body.</li><li>Chemical injuries.</li><li>Neonatal conjunctivitis.</li></ul></li><li>Assessment of a person with red eye involves taking a history and performing an examination.<ul><li>History should include onset and duration of symptoms, whether these are unilateral or bilateral, associated symptoms (visual changes, pain, foreign body sensation, discharge or photophobia), use of contact lenses, any trauma or chemical exposure, previous episodes, and relevant past medical history and medication. </li><li>Examination should include inspection, assessment of visual acuity, fluorescein examination, and pupil reactions. </li></ul></li><li>Features in the history and examination which can indicate there is a serious cause of the person's red eye, and therefore that same day ophthalmology assessment is required, include:<ul><li>Reduced visual acuity or deep pain within the eye.</li><li>Unilateral red eye.</li><li>Contact lens use.</li><li>Photophobia.</li><li>High-velocity injury.</li><li>Chemical eye injury.</li><li>Ciliary injection.</li><li>Fluorescein staining of the cornea.</li><li>Unequal or misshapen pupils, abnormal pupillary reactions or painful pupillary constriction.</li><li>Red, sticky eye in an infant in the first 28 days of life (this can be discussed for opinion with paediatrics or ophthalmology).</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 7fd9b01f-7666-4a57-9e79-c437efd6ae9b --><!-- end item 80994f4c-606c-4b3d-bf4a-9a833e4a1e3a -->","topic":{"id":"f0a8e60e-0d78-5c3f-a192-dcd74c022871","topicId":"4bf93da0-c44a-46ac-a037-45acff9fe791","topicName":"Red eye","slug":"red-eye","aliases":[],"chapters":[{"id":"5231497c-9015-54fd-b4f6-0c15ee18af82","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"a41597cd-e612-52f7-b538-4b20402de6a8","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","subChapters":[]},{"id":"57836fbe-7a46-5d83-841e-813fc255d3ec","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","subChapters":[{"id":"a066d0df-07cb-5be9-bd3a-1ebec9aa6eee","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"b6901286-4060-54a4-bbfe-bdd981552747","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"6fdd5084-2038-5097-b0c9-f8f1f876aace","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","subChapters":[{"id":"e06aa917-5d50-57ea-874e-58fa8fc8e32f","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"5bd63347-ad8b-525e-b1be-e72ca66b382d","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"a2844bfb-f4eb-5118-b14f-c887ded48f69","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"9f26f95e-7b2d-5b64-b441-c3d6480df0f2","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"d2f70980-9d95-575e-8b38-48391bd5b07a","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - options for local implementation"},{"id":"7eb32fc9-cb00-5ae1-bc0c-948d9494b9d5","slug":"nice-quality-sta